{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655552"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:03:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:03:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18674"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18674"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11406"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62295"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10306"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26430"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA neurologist tests a patient\u0027s patellar tendon reflex by tapping just below the knee with a reflex hammer. This causes a brief contraction of the quadriceps muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the neural pathway of this stretch reflex?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Muscle spindle to gamma motor neuron to intrafusal muscle fibre","Muscle spindle to interneuron to gamma motor neuron","Golgi tendon organ to alpha motor neuron to muscle spindle","Golgi tendon organ to interneuron to extrafusal muscle fibre","Muscle spindle to alpha motor neuron to extrafusal muscle fibre"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pathway involves \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscle spindle to alpha motor neuron to extrafusal muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E. When the patellar tendon is stretched, muscle spindles detect the change in muscle length. 1a afferent neurons carry this signal to the spinal cord where they directly synapse with alpha motor neurons in the ventral horn. These motor neurons then activate extrafusal muscle fibres, causing the quadriceps to contract.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGolgi tendon organ to alpha motor neuron to muscle spindle\u003C/strong\u003E - Golgi tendon organs detect tension not stretch, and muscle spindles are sensory not contractile structures\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle spindle to interneuron to gamma motor neuron\u003C/strong\u003E - The stretch reflex is monosynaptic and does not involve interneurons\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGolgi tendon organ to interneuron to extrafusal muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E - Golgi tendon organs typically inhibit rather than activate muscle contraction\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle spindle to gamma motor neuron to intrafusal muscle fibre\u003C/strong\u003E - Gamma motor neurons adjust muscle spindle sensitivity but do not directly cause muscle contraction\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThis monosynaptic reflex arc is one of the simplest neural circuits and forms the basis of clinical tendon reflex testing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The stretch reflex is a monosynaptic spinal reflex that maintains muscle tone and posture.","Muscle spindles detect changes in muscle length and initiate the stretch reflex via 1a afferent neurons.","Alpha motor neurons in the ventral horn directly innervate extrafusal muscle fibres to cause muscle contraction."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62295"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18674"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62295"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T13:00:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T13:01:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11406"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76796"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag